choices.text:
that I am too thin, and people often ask me “have you ever eat?”. If only I had your problem! At first, as a teenager, I withdraw myself to protect myself. I wasn’t letting anyone close because I didn’t want to be hurt. But, then I acted as if I wasn’t careful at all because of self-pity. I made mistakes, I hooked up with people, I “acted cool” but underneath all of the layers, I was really hurt. These past few years, in Houghton, it’s been difficult for me to have healthy relationships with men (so, it hasn’t been going well…). But eventually I started acting like I didn’t know what to do in order to protect my heart. I leaned on the Lord. It’s there that I learned that I cannot protect my heart for long, and even if it’s painful, I will never be fulfilled until I open my heart to the Lord and to people.

It’s not that hard to practice these–try taking a walk in the afternoon and watch how people communicate happiness. Even talking about these things will allow you to connect with people!

Communication brings happiness. Take notes of you day, and think that “if I kept paper and pen that day, I would always remember it. That is happiness.”
